%N A388038 a(n) is the number of steps to reach 1 when the Sisyphus sequence (A350877) begins with n, or -1 if 1 is never reached.
%C A388038 Rules of the Sisyphus sequence (A350877): if the last term, s(m), is even, s(m+1) = s(m)/2; otherwise, s(m+1) = s(m) + the smallest prime not yet added.
%C A388038 Beginning the Sisyphus sequence with the seed 1008973 runs more than 2^30 terms without reaching 1 (A388141). Michael S. Branicky found that A388141(3584971546) = 1. - _Michael De Vlieger_, Sep 14 2025
%H A388038 James C. McMahon, <a href="/A388038/b388038.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A388038 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A388038/a388038.png">Scatterplot of first 65536 terms.</a>
%H A388038 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="http://vincico.com/seq/a350877.html">The Sisyphus Sequence</a>, 2022.
%e A388038 For n = 1, a(n) = 0, no steps are required to reach 1.
%e A388038 For n = 3, a(n) = 5.
%e A388038   Step 1: 3 is odd, the next term is 3 + 2 (first prime) = 5.
%e A388038   Step 2: 5 is odd, the next term is 5 + 3 (next prime) = 8.
%e A388038   Step 3: 8 is even, the next term is 8/2 = 4.
%e A388038   Step 4: 4 is even, the next term is 4/2 = 2.
%e A388038   Step 5: 2 is even, the next term is 2/2 = 1.
%t A388038 a[n_]:=Module[{s={n},p=2,c=1},While[s[[-1]]!=1,If[OddQ[s[[-1]]],AppendTo[s,s[[-1]]+p];p=NextPrime[p],AppendTo[s,s[[-1]]/2]];c++];c-1];Array[a,67]
%o A388038 (Python)
%o A388038 from sympy import nextprime
%o A388038 def sisyphus(start): # generator of Sisyphus sequence beginning at start
%o A388038     an, p = start, 1
%o A388038     while True: yield an; an = an+(p:=nextprime(p)) if an&1 else an>>1
%o A388038 def a(n): return next(k for k, t in enumerate(sisyphus(n)) if t == 1)
%o A388038 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 68)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Sep 16 2025
